  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Strengthening Health System to Improve Access to Health Care Services Among Rohingya Refugees in Ukhiya and Teknaf-Cox&apos;s Bazar Bangladesh</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Since the influx of over 700,000 Rohingya refugees into Cox&apos;s Bazar commenced on 25th August 2018, the health system in the district has been placed under enormous strain due to the increase in population and associated diversity of public health issues. IOM remains as a key health agency, supporting 23 health facilities and taking the lead in managing emergency and chronic referrals from community level to secondary/tertiary care facilities.  IOM will continue to improve the capacity and quality of healthcare services to the Rohingya refugee community through increasing the number of fully-equipped secondary health care facilities, number of facilities providing basic emergency obstetric and new-born care and strengthen the capacity of the referral system from camps to secondary level facilities. Through development of these elements of the response, IOM will ensure continued support to the community through the subsequent increase in the resilience and capacity of the health system and its stakeholder.</narrative>
  </description>
